Which is the cause of your problems. You should use the build file provided with the project. In this case the `pom.xml` to build the artifact. You should run `./mvnw package` which will create the proper jar file with the dependencies and proper files. 

If you do it the way you do, you will only get a jar with the classes, with no repacked structure nor dependencies. You basically skip the whole Spring Boot thing. 

**Pro Tip** Cleanup your `pom.xml` as there are some discrepancies in there. 

1. Remove the `maven-compiler-plugin` and specify the version through properties. Spring Boot already sets up this plugin for you
2. Remove the `version` of the `spring-boot-maven-plugin` you want to use the same version as the `parent` you provided. 
3. Remove the `junit` dependency, this is already included in `spring-boot-starter-test`
4. Remove the `version` from the `mysql` dependency, it is an old one and Spring Boot manages a proper, recent version.
5. Remove the `version` of the `spring-boot-starter-test` dependency, use the same version as the parent. If you leave it like this and upgrade the parent you have a version mismatch.

